observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed to - 

xxx;

xxx;

consider the one-time cleansing of assets as cited under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for the detailed procedures in regard with the disposition of non-existing/ missing PPEs and/or derecognition of the same without available record of accountability; and

direct the Municipal Accountant to – 

xxx; and

immediately update PPELC.

We also reiterated prior year’s recommendation and Management agreed to –

instruct the GSO to prepare, maintain, and update Property Cards for all PPEs;

We recommended and Management agreed to –

xxx; 

direct the Municipal Accountant to (i) xxx; 
(ii) prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers (SLs) to support of the RPT and SET accounts in order to have proper reconciliation with the MTO regularly; and (iii) after reconciliation with the MTO, make necessary adjustment to reflect the correct amount of RPT/SET Receivable; and

require the Municipal Treasurer to (i) include all of the delinquent taxpayers in the Certified List of All Real Property Tax Delinquencies every year end; and (ii) implement procedures and strategies on how to further improve collection efficiency relative to real property tax.

We also reiterated prior year’s recommendation for Management to instruct the Municipal Treasurer to (i) xxx; and (ii) include remarks/statement regarding the reason/s for non-collection or non-payment in the certified list of all real property tax delinquencies which remained uncollected or unpaid for at least one year to the request for assistance in the enforcement of the remedies for collection submitted to the Sanggunian.

We commended Management for developing a comprehensive data coverage on GAD Database System, strengthening its GAD Focal Point System and compliance with mandatory allocation for GAD PPAs.  

We recommended and Management agreed, through its GFPS to (a) xxx; 
(b) ensure accurate reporting of GAD AR by incorporating changes made to the GAD Budget from realignments and supplemental budget; 
(c) inform the concerned DILG Office in writing regarding the changes in the DILG-endorsed GPB; and 
(d) ensure that the PPAs are in alignment with the GAD objectives of truly addressing gender issues towards gender equality and women empowerment.

We reiterated the following recommendations and Management agreed to instruct the –  

Inventory Committee -

conduct complete annual physical count of PPE; 

reconcile the actual count and the existing inventory records, if there is any and submit complete and duly signed RPCPPE to the Office of the Auditor not later than the prescribed deadline by the Manual; and 
identify the reasons for the differences noted before making any adjustment;

OIC-GSO 
cause the preparation and maintenance of complete and updated Property Cards (PCs) to enable reconciliation with the general ledger balances and the inventory report; and 
take the necessary action to identify all unserviceable government properties and prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) so that proper disposal could be undertaken;

Appraisal and Disposal Committee 
inspect unserviceable equipment and property to verify justification for disposal;
set the final appraised value of all disposable properties; 
recommend to the Local Chief Executive (LCE) for approval, the manner of disposal; and (iv) conduct public bidding for the sale of disposable property on an ‘as is, where is basis’ and recommend corresponding award thereof; and

Municipal Accountant 
make necessary adjusting entry to record the derecognition of properties after disposal and correct the balances presented in the financial statements; and 

submit PAR/ICS of the laptop computers and printers issued to DepEd.

We also recommended the Management to follow the guidelines set forth in the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts per COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended and Management agreed to instruct the BAC to 
strictly follow the proper procedures set forth under RA No. 9184, specifically, in the detailed evaluation and post-qualification of the bids; 

ensure that all documents required are thoroughly reviewed before determining the LCRB in order to create a more reliable procurement process; 

(c) send invitation to observers in all stages of procurement; 

(d) adhere to the posting requirements set under RIRR of RA No. 9184 to promote effective competition and transparency in the procurement process; and 

(e) submit the documents relative to Supply and delivery of IT Equipment and Office Supplies for DepEd, Morong District to avoid further audit action on the transaction.

We recommended and Management agreed to – 

ensure that the area for waste bins is secured to prevent unauthorized access of persons within the area;


ensure the completeness of documentary requirements supporting the claims of Metro Clark for residual waste collection services.

We reiterated our prior years’ recommendations and Management agreed to instruct the Municipal Accountant to (a) strictly monitor and conduct regular and periodic verification, analysis, and validation of the existence of the receivables and payable accounts; 

(b) conduct reconciliation of the balances to source agencies in case of payable accounts and; 

(c) request for write-off of uncollectible receivables and payables from the books of accounts to the Commission on Audit supported by documents required by the Circular.

We recommended and Management agreed to –

ensure the (i) preparation of RPCI in the required format as certified correct by the Inventory Committee, attested by the Audit Team’s representative and approved by the Head of the Agency and 

(ii) submission of RPCI to the Audit Team for audit and validation thereof; 



(ii) use perpetual inventory method instead of direct expense in order to properly account all the unused supplies and/or materials as of a given date;


require the Inventory Custodian/AO to update SCs daily and prepare SSMI to be submitted every week or at least once a month to the Municipal Accountant together with RIS or equivalent document so that issuances will be computed and recorded by the latter;

instruct the Municipal Treasurer to apply for the fidelity bond of Inventory Custodians who are regular employees of the Municipality.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical inventory of all the Municipality’s PPE and prepare and submit the required report thereon, in proper form and within the prescribed period. Any discrepancy between the inventory report and the accounting and property records should be investigated and make the necessary adjustments where the error was committed;
b. Municipal Accountant and the GSO to ensure that PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards were being maintained, respectively. Both records should always be updated and reconciled;
c. Officials concerned to submit the required additional documents to support the request to write off the properties razed/damaged by the fire; and
d. Municipal Accountant to continue exerting efforts to trace back and substantiate the old balances of the PPE accounts in order to provide the correct depreciation for each type of properties of the Municipality.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation to require the: 

(a)	Inventory Committee to conduct complete annual physical count of PPE and inventory and submit RPCPPE and RPCI, respectively, to the Office of the Auditor not later than the prescribed deadline stated in the Manual;

(b)	Accounting Office update and maintain PPE and Real Property Ledger Cards and the GSO cause the preparation and maintenance of Property Cards to enable reconciliation with the general ledger balances and the inventory report;

(c)	OIC-GSO take the necessary action to identify all unserviceable government properties and prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) so that proper disposal could be undertaken; and

(d)	Municipal Accountant make the necessary adjusting entry to record the derecognition of properties after disposal.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation to require the:
(a)	Inventory Committee to conduct complete annual physical count of PPE and inventory and submit RPCPPE and RCPI, respectively, to the Office of the Auditor not later than the prescribed deadline stated in the Manual;
(b)	Accounting Office update and maintain PPE and Real Property Ledger Cards and the GSO cause the preparation and maintenance of Property Cards to enable reconciliation with the general ledger balances and the inventory report;
(c)	OIC-GSO take the necessary action to identify all unserviceable government properties and prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) so that proper disposal could be undertaken; and
(d)	Municipal Accountant make the necessary adjusting entry to record the derecognition of properties after disposal.

We strongly reiterated that Management compel:

the Inventory Committee to conduct a complete inventory of all the inventory and fixed assets of the Municipality,  prepare and submit the report thereon,  reconcile the inventory report with the accounting and property records and investigate and effect the necessary adjustments  for any discrepancies noted;


the Accountant to exert more efforts in locating records of prior years’ acquisitions of  properties to establish the  details of the PPE accounts, and make the necessary reclassifying/adjusting entries to correct the erroneous entries made, including the recording of the properties funded under the BUB; 

the acting General Services Officer to maintain  an up-dated  property cards and ARE as a counter check as to the accuracy of the accounting records,  facilitate  inventory taking and determination of the responsible/accountable  officials/employees for the equipment; and 


the official concerned to secure from the Rizal Provincial Government, the donor of the Mitsubishi Montero, the Deed of Donation for the vehicle,  in order that its cost  could be recorded  in the books of accounts and as a proof of ownership of the vehicle by the Municipality.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
1. Accountable Officers of the lost/destroyed properties to submit immediately to the  Auditor  the  request  for  relief  from  property  accountability, duly supported with all the  required  documentations, so that they maybe relieved from any liability over those properties, and the cost of such could thereafter be dropped  from  the books  of  accounts  of  the municipality;
2. General Service Office to immediately  record  the  deliveries  of supplies and property based on the Acceptance and Inspection Report (AIR) and other supporting documents and forward the same to the Municipal Accountant for preparation of Disbursement Voucher and recording of deliveries to appropriate ledger cards;
2.a.   General Service Office and the Accounting Office to maintain updated and complete stock cards/property cards and ARE and property ledger cards, respectively to facilitate inventory taking, reconciliation between the property and accounting records and verification of the PPE accounts. Determine the officials/employees to whom  the  equipment  were  issued,  and   issue   the   corresponding Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) for  each  property  to pinpoint  the direct person accountable and responsible thereon.  Moreover, renew all ARE every three years to update signature and information like designation/position or assignment of the  holder  of  each  item  listed  in  the RPCPPE;
3.   Municipal Accountant to continue exerting efforts in tracing back prior years’ acquisition of Property, Plant and Equipment to have a complete details of the fixed asset accounts so that  the  corresponding depreciation could be computed, to present fairly the true value of the depreciable fixed asset accounts;
4.  Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of physical inventory of all the property, plant and equipment; and submit the properly accomplished Inventory Reports as require under Section 57 of the MNGAS for LGUs Volume II and reconcile the Reports with the accounting and property records, investigate any discrepancy that may exist thereafter and effect the necessary corrections where needed; and
5. General Services Officer and the Municipal Accountant to coordinate each other to facilitate the recording of the cost of the Mitsubishi Montero in the books of accounts.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor requires the:
Municipal Accountant to work back and exert extra effort to establish the reliability of the account;
Municipal Accountant to make reconciliation with the accounting unit of the Provincial Government of Rizal regarding  prior years’ share in the Real Property Tax;
Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to process the immediate remittance of whatever is found due to the Province, so that it could immediately use such additional funds.
